\f0\fs24 \cf0 Marguerite turned the key at half past seven, same as every morning. The bookshop door swung inward with its familiar creak\'97a sound she had never bothered to fix because it announced the day\'92s beginning better than any clock.\
\
Inside, the air was thick with the smell of old paper and binding glue, a scent she imagined would outlast her. She set her canvas bag on the counter and switched on the lamp beside the register. Its amber glow caught the spines of a hundred novels arranged in careful rows along the front table.\
\
\'93Another Tuesday,\'94 she said to no one.\
\
She filled the kettle in the back room and stood waiting for it to boil, watching the harbor through the narrow window. Frost had settled on the quay stones overnight. The fishing boats rocked gently at their moorings, their hulls dark against the pale morning water.\
\
The kettle clicked. She poured her tea, carried it to the front of the bookshop, and unlocked the display case. The day, she decided, could begin.}